3. Cross Entropy Loss
Definition

Cross Entropy Loss is the standard loss function used for Classification Problems.

It measures how different the predicted probability distribution is from the true class.

Applications

Used in:

Cat vs Dog Classification
Spam Detection
Digit Recognition (MNIST)
Disease Classification
Image Classification
Important Note

When using

nn.CrossEntropyLoss()

Do NOT apply Softmax manually.

CrossEntropyLoss() internally applies LogSoftmax before calculating the loss.

PyTorch
criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()

outputs = model(images)

loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
4. Gradient Descent
Definition

Gradient Descent is an optimization algorithm used to minimize the loss function by updating the model's weights.

The goal is to find the weights that produce the smallest possible loss.

Formula
New Weight=Old Weight−Learning Rate×Gradient
Working
Forward Pass
      ↓
Calculate Loss
      ↓
Backpropagation
      ↓
Compute Gradients
      ↓
Update Weights
      ↓
Repeat
5. Optimizer
Definition

An Optimizer is an algorithm that updates the neural network's weights using the calculated gradients.

Its purpose is to minimize the loss function.

Without an optimizer, the model cannot learn.

Popular Optimizers
SGD
Adam
RMSprop
AdamW
Adagrad
6. Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD)
Definition

SGD updates the model parameters using gradients calculated during backpropagation.

PyTorch
optimizer = torch.optim.SGD(
    model.parameters(),
    lr=0.01
)
Advantages
Simple algorithm
Low memory usage
Easy to understand
Widely used
Disadvantages
Slow convergence
Can oscillate around the minimum
Sensitive to learning rate
7. Adam Optimizer
Definition

Adam (Adaptive Moment Estimation) is an advanced optimization algorithm that automatically adapts the learning rate for each parameter using gradient statistics.

It combines the advantages of Momentum and RMSProp.

PyTorch
optimizer = torch.optim.Adam(
    model.parameters(),
    lr=0.001
)
Advantages
Faster convergence
Stable training
Less hyperparameter tuning
Works well for most deep learning tasks
Disadvantages
Uses more memory than SGD
Sometimes generalizes slightly worse than SGD on certain vision tasks
8. SGD vs Adam
Feature	SGD	Adam
Speed	Slower	Faster
Adaptive Learning Rate	No	Yes
Memory Usage	Low	Higher
Training Stability	Moderate	High
Beginner Friendly	Moderate	Excellent
9. Learning Rate
Definition

The Learning Rate (lr) determines the size of each weight update during training.

It controls how quickly or slowly the model learns.

Effects
Very Small Learning Rate
Slow learning
Longer training time
Stable updates
Very Large Learning Rate
Overshoots the minimum
Training becomes unstable
Loss may increase
Optimal Learning Rate
Faster convergence
Stable learning
Better final accuracy
Example
optimizer = torch.optim.Adam(
    model.parameters(),
    lr=0.001
)
10. Learning Rate Scheduler
Definition

A Learning Rate Scheduler automatically changes the learning rate during training.

Usually, it gradually decreases the learning rate after certain epochs.

Why Use It?

Large learning rates help during early training.

Small learning rates help fine-tune the model near the optimum.

This often results in:

Better convergence
Lower loss
Improved accuracy
Example
scheduler = StepLR(
    optimizer,
    step_size=10,
    gamma=0.1
)

Every 10 epochs,

Old LR × 0.1

becomes the new learning rate.

